@DATABASE FreshIcons-Help
@$VER: FreshIcon-Bugfixing 1.3.1 ( 6. April 1997 )
@AUTHOR: Christian Taulien of Strange Intelligence
@NODE Main "FreshIcons V 1.2"
Written by Christian Taulien of Strange Intelligence

    @{b}@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 14}@{bpen 4} FreshIconsV1.2 - Problemsolving @{bpen 0}@{FG TEXT}@{ub}

    This  file  describes  problem-situations  rised   up   through   wrong
    installation of the FreshIconsV1.2-Package

    But: Don't panic!

    @{"The Colors are wrong." LINK "pb1"}
    @{"The Amiga deadlocks while booting." LINK "pb2"}
    @{"On 8-Color Workbenches the icons look green." LINK "pb3"}
    @{"After changing the Workbench-Screen the Colors are wrong." LINK "pb4"}
    @{"FreshIconizer contains no logo in its informationwindow." LINK "pb5"}
    @{"While booting the screenmode is switched twice or more." LINK "pb6"}
    @{"Drag&Drop doesn't work with drawer icons" LINK "pb7"}
    @{"Progs use FreshColors although LockFreshPens is not running." LINK "pb8"}
    @{"The picture is not displayed in the wanted screenmode" LINK "pb9"}
    @{"The software-installscript abort directly after their start." LINK "pb10"}
    @{"After installation the workbench-icons are still the same." LINK "pb11"}

    @{"You should not..." LINK "ysn"}
@ENDNODE
@NODE "pb1" "Problem1"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 8}1. Problem:@{FG TEXT}
    The colors are wrong.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 13}Possible reason:@{FG TEXT}
    a) LockFreshPens was not (or wrong) started in your user-startup.
    b) LockFreshPens was started,  indeed, but it quit  immediately  itself
       because in the  ENV:-drawer the enviroment-variable  PALETTESET with
       a value of FRESH already existed.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 11}Solution:@{FG TEXT}
    a)
    Look for the LockFreshPens command to be present in  the  user-startup.
    If  not  then either install the package again (userdefined and without
    icons to speed up this) or type this at the end of the user-startup  in
    your s:-drawer:

    @{b}run >nil: C:LockFreshPens quiet patch magic8 >nil:@{ub}

    b)
    To test this, type in a shell:
        @{b}List ENVARC:PAL#?@{ub}
    After pressing the return-key, all resetsave enviromentvariables begin-
    ning with PAL will be listet. If you find an entry named  PALETTESET
    in this list type furthermore:
        @{b}Type ENVARC:PALETTESET@{ub}
    If now the word FRESH is put out, the reason b is the right one.  Type:
        @{b}Delete ENVARC:PALETTESET@{ub}
    to delete the variable. The next reboot should work well. If anyone has
    the same problem after the 2nd reboot  has propably configured his girl
    so,  that ENV: and ENVARC: are  both the same.  You should not do this!
    A further  ugly  result of doing so is saving a preferences-setting in-
    stead of just using it, because using  means saving  to ENV: and saving
    means saving to ENVARC: which  is copied everytime you reboot into ENV:
    (which is normally lying in RAM:ENV) It is advised to reconfigure  this
    thing. If you dont want to change that, it shall be told, that a Delete
    ENV:PALETTESET call in your user-startup  before  calling LockFreshPens
    should fix this problem too.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "pb2" "Problem2"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 8}2. Problem:@{FG TEXT}
    The Amiga deadlock while booting.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 13}Possible reason:@{FG TEXT}
    LockFeshPens was started with out the run command.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 11}Solution:@{FG TEXT}
    Load the file s:user-startup in an editor (for example  ED  or  GoldED)
    and  write "run >nil:" (with out quotes) before the LockFreshPens-Call.
    After that the edited line looks that way:

    @{b}run >nil: C:LockFreshPens quiet patch magic8 >nil:@{ub}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "pb3" "Problem3"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 8}3. Problem:@{FG TEXT}
    On 8-Color-Workbenches the icon look green.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 13}Possible reason:@{FG TEXT}
    LockFreshPens was started without the "magic8" parameter

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 11}Solution:@{FG TEXT}
    Load the file s:user-startup in an editor (for example  ED  or  GoldED)
    and  append  the  "magic8" argument to the LockFreshPens call. (without
    quotes) After that the edited line looks that way:

    @{b}run >nil: C:LockFreshPens quiet patch magic8 >nil:@{ub}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "pb4" "Problem4"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 8}4. Problem:@{FG TEXT}
    Nach Umstellen der Worbkench mit dem  Screenmode-Voreinsteller  stimmen
    die Farben nicht mehr.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 13}Possible reason:@{FG TEXT}
    LockFreshPens was started without the "patch" parameter.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 11}Solution:@{FG TEXT}
    Load the file s:user-startup in an editor (for example  ED  or  GoldED)
    and  append  the  "patch"  argument to the LockFreshPens call. (without
    quotes) After that the edited line looks that way:

    @{b}run >nil: C:LockFreshPens quiet patch magic8 >nil:@{ub}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "pb5" "Problem5"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 8}5. Problem:@{FG TEXT}
    FreshIconizer contains no logo in the information-window.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 13}Possible reason:@{FG TEXT}
    LockFreshPens was not started. Therefore the ENV-Variable  "PALETTESET"
    containing the value "FRESH" is not present.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 11}Solution:@{FG TEXT}
    Call the LockFreshPens command in your user-startup. Normally  this  is
    done by the installation-script.

    This line looks that way:

    @{b}run >nil: C:LockFreshPens quiet patch magic8 >nil:@{ub}

@ENDNODE
@NODE "pb6" "Problem6"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 8}6. Problem:@{FG TEXT}
    While booting the screenmode is switched more than once or the Workbench
    opens and closes its screen several times.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 13}Possible reason:@{FG TEXT}
    In your startup-sequence the user-startup is executed before the iprefs
    program.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 11}Solution:@{FG TEXT}
    In the default-startup-sequence of the workbench is  that  not.  (First
    the  iprefs  is  called  and then the user-startup is executed.) To fix
    this problem load the startup-sequence in an editor (for example ED  or
    GoldED)  and  change  it  so,  that  iprefs  is  called  first.  In the
    user-startup the LockFreshPens is started which reqires  iprefs  to  be
    called already.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "pb7" "Problem7"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 8}7. Problem:@{FG TEXT}
    You drop an icon over an iconbox of FreshIconizer and nothing happens.
    (Neither the source nor the destination-box).

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 13}Possible reason:@{FG TEXT}
    Indeed there is an icons of a drawer, but not the  drawer  itself.  The
    Workbench  does  not  test  whether  a drawer really exists and so such
    things can  happen.  These  icons  can  only  be  drag&droppen  in  the
    workbench  windows. To test whether this is the reason for your problem
    just doubleclick the icon. If no drawer  exists  the  Workbench  states
    that.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 11}Solution:@{FG TEXT}
    Create a drawer for that icon. This is done as described here:
    With the Shell, an example:

    The icon is in                  Work:Pictures/Comics/new.info
    Change to that directory:       1.SYS:>cd Work:Pictures/Comics
    Create the drawer:              1.Work:Pictures/Comics>makedir new

    Or via a filemanager as DirOpus, Filer or so.

    Change to that directory, an create the drawer with  the  button  meant
    for this purpose.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "pb8" "Problem8"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 8}8. Problem:@{FG TEXT}
    Program seem to use the FreshColors although LockFreshPens wasn't started.
    and so the FreshColors can't be active.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 13}Possible reason:@{FG TEXT}
    In the  ENVARC:  (not  ENV:)  could  exist  a  file  named  PALETTESET.
    Everytime  you  boot  this ENVARC: drawer is completely copied into the
    ENV: drawer. So if this File exists there, then everytime you boot  the
    PALETTESET   ENV-Variable   is   present.   So   the  programs  believe
    LockFreshPens was started. Variables in the ENV-drawer are nothing  but
    files.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 11}Solution:@{FG TEXT}
    Delete the PALETTESET file in your ENVARC: and your ENV: drawer.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "pb9" "Problem9"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 8}8. Problem:@{FG TEXT}
    The picture is not displayed in the wanted screenmode

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 13}Possible reasons:@{FG TEXT}
    a)  A screenpromoter-program forces CAFIC to do so.
    b)  The tooltype SCREENMODEID in the CAFIC-icon is not specified right.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 11}Solution:@{FG TEXT}
    a)  If the reason is a screenpromoter program you should be able to
        solve the problem
    b)  The tooltype SCREENMODEID is for telling CAFIC which screemode to
        use. A 0 or disabling this tooltype is for taking the screenmodeid
        given in the picturefile. If you are not familiar with the modeid-
        numbers specify a zero.
@ENDNODE
@NODE "pb10" "Problem10"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 8}10. Problem:@{FG TEXT}
    Directly after starting the software-set installation an error is re-
    ported and the installation is aborted.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 13}Possible reason:@{FG TEXT}
    You have either no or an old version of the installer in your C:-Drawer.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 11}Solution:@{FG TEXT}
    In the drawer of the uninstalled version of FreshIconsV1.1 is a copy of
    the required version the installer. Please copy it into your C:-Drawer.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "pb11" "Problem11"
@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 8}11. Problem:@{FG TEXT}
    After installation the workbench-icons are still the same.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 13}Possible reason:@{FG TEXT}
    This seems to be no error/problem. You just forgot something:
    The main-installation-script simply installs the FreshIcons-package
    itself. No icons will be modified after it is done.

@{FG HIGHLIGHT}@{apen 11}Solution:@{FG TEXT}
    You need to run the Workbench-icon-installscript in the drawer:
        "FreshIconsV1.1/Icons/Software-Sets/WB/"
    in your wanted language. The rest is up to the script.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "ysn" "You should not..."

    You should NOT:

    · use FastIPrefs in a version before 40.17
    · use AmigaGuide-datatype in a version before 40.12
    · use MUI before 3.x

    and :-)
    · play Cricket
    · meet Wanagi Wachipi
@ENDNODE

